players.note: Joe Flacco's arrival completely stabilizes this offense. Chase has 25 targets and 16 catches in Flacco's first two outings, and the ROS schedule lacks any top-10 pressure defenses. His ceiling weeks are back. Even after a blow-up, he's still under-priced.

He's the clear air-yards and route leader (100% route rate, 44% share) but has only box-score duds to show for it. With Cole Kmet hurt and positive matchups ahead, Odunze's usage is screaming buy-low — he ranks 15th in XPPG among WRs.
Air yards trending up; PFF's 13th-highest WR grade. Even in a quiet week, usage supports WR2 floor. Already past the bye and facing a friendly stretch (GB, IND, LAC). Hold or minor buy.
Fifteen targets from Herbert (9-67, 27%) with 113 air yards and three end-zone looks. Slot-dominant role and the Vikings' defense next (dead-last vs slot). Clear buy-low WR2 candidate.

A quiet week hides the fact that he still leads the Panthers in expected points per game (19th overall). Andy Dalton's promotion boosts WR efficiency, and McMillan has shown chemistry with Dalton before. Buy-low ahead of a soft Buffalo matchup.
Still producing but efficiency fueled by Carson Wentz. With J.J. McCarthy due back in Week 9, regression is coming. One more spike week possible — sell right after it hits.

Stefon Diggs continues to dominate in the Pats offense...after he broke out in Week 4. 10-146 on 12 targets (40% target share) in Week 5. He's back to pre-injury form, and the WR1 rest of the season for New England. And he is so overdue for a TD score. So even though he is coming off a meh game, he is still a BUY. Kayshon Boutte came away with the big game, going 5-92-2 on five targets. 
Diggs wasn't terrible - 3-28 on three targets - because his biggest play of 51 yards was taken off on an OPI call. Refs were BAD in this game.
Don't worry about Diggs. In fact, use this as a reason to BUY LOW after the two other NE WRs popped in the box score this week. After Week 6, Diggs is still PFF's 6th-highest graded WR - and he'd be averaging over 3 yards per route run had the 51-yard catch stood.
Another injury (heel) and volatile weekly usage. With McLaurin returning soon and Mariota/backup QB flux, this is your final off-ramp. Sell before the inevitable missed-time stretch.

Assuming that Ricky Pearsall's health is in check...I want to buy low on him. Use the Kendrick Bourne-Mac Jones connection to buy low on Ricky Pearsall. Brock Purdy will be back under center at some point. Jauan Jennings is also no long-term bet to stay healthy, given all the injuries he is playing through. His injuries seemed to hamper his production. Given he caught just one pass for 7 yards on three targets in Week 6.
If Pearsall starts practicing this week. Smash buy. PFF's 15th-highest graded WR in four games played.

Two catches on eight targets, 40% air yards but zero chemistry with Kyler Murray looming. PFF's 65th-graded WR; WR43 in XPPG. The post-bye slate (DAL, SEA, SF) is brutal. Sell before the name cachet fades.

Six catches for 85 yards total over two games; now banged up and facing an erratic QB situation. He's been turned into a gadget runner (three carries inside the 10). Ship out while trade-rumor buzz remains.
Post-bye add; 6-plus targets in back-to-back games, 23% share.
